properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued January 28 at 10:41PM AKST by NWS Juneau AK
properties.description:
A fast-moving and very strong storm system will move into the
southeast Gulf of Alaska late Wednesday night and cross the
Panhandle Thursday morning.

Immediately along and south of the track of the storm, very strong
southerly winds are expected, shifting abruptly to the west as the
storm passes. These winds may down trees and powerlines as well as
cause damage to fragile infrastructure along the coast. Should the
low pass around the time of high tide, some coastal flooding is
possible.

Just to the north of the track of the storm, a period of very
heavy snowfall is possible, followed by a rapid increase in the
southerly winds.

At this time, the forecast calls for the strongest winds to be
roughly along and south of a line from Sitka to Tenakee Springs to
Point Bishop with heavy snowfall possible north of this line
including Juneau, Gustavus, and Hoonah. There are still some
significant track and timing differences that could play a huge
role in the weather impacts across the region. People are advised
to stay weather-aware and keep informed with the latest forecasts
and potential watches, warnings, and advisories from the National
Weather Service in Juneau.

NWSheadline: POWERFUL WINTER STORM EXPECTED TO AFFECT SOUTHEAST ALASKA LATE WEDNESDAY NIGHT INTO THURSDAY MORNING
